The Comprehensive Crisis in Lebanon
Beirut — Looking back, financial crises usually seem to have warning signs; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
Lebanon is in the same situation now, with an anticipated crisis having plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been sustained by external borrowing, which inevitably led to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, the inflow of external capital had to stop. This point came in late 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
This sudden stoppage of capital has brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit is as high as 25% of GDP, and its export base is too small to even cover the costs of necessary imports.
The second issue is fiscal.
Lebanon's public debt now totals over 150% of GDP.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of economic decline, with the budget deficit already significant, reaching 10% of GDP in 2019 and still rapidly expanding.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Major banks, as the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have heavily invested in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their portfolios), and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises together are pushing Lebanon's economy into deep crisis.
Companies eager to borrow and import have started laying off workers or closing down completely.
Economic decline could lead to a Lebanese depression.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but remittances, which are attracted to invest due to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate pegged to the dollar.
So it is not surprising to see signs of "Dutch disease" everywhere: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national savings rate to an unlikely level — 3% of GDP.
Inequality is high and continues to rise.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, greatly weakening the tradable sectors.
Due to the lack of export goods and services, Lebanon has been losing its educated youth.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows have allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have siphoned off wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated patronage-based ruling group.
Although this has ensured political stability in this otherwise chaotic region, it has failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is intermittent and unreliable, while the broader macroeconomic challenges have remained completely unresolved.
The financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country's regime has responded to Lebanon's economic problems in a manner that has overwhelmingly favored the elites, indicating that the crisis may ultimately be "solved" with the support of the poor and middle class, and further consolidate sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the major shareholders of each bank, which include ruling politicians, to decide how to withdraw cash in limited amounts.
In practice, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens find it difficult to access their deposits.
Additionally, the central bank reduced deposit rates but has not lowered public debt rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite declining international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its major foreign debt owed to domestic banks.
There are indications that it may begin selling state assets at fire-sale prices to elite-connected entities.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, while elites are allowed to obtain dollars at a low exchange rate, whereas ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly declining market exchange rate. The current market exchange rate is now discounted by 40%.
When the country starts printing lira to pay public sector workers' salaries, depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been using lira to pay interest on dollar deposits (which account for more than 80% of total deposits), thereby creating conditions for inflation to eliminate public debt.
As the cost of debt reduction is shifted to savers through the "liraization" of holdings, banks' equity is basically spared.
If this situation becomes reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decline in real wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The emigration of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the diaspora community — which this system relies on — will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a system of poor people, who can be controlled by increasingly cheaper shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation as Venezuela.
In contrast, the establishment of the new republic by the revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
The revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, rather than abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and that performance, effective management, and social justice should replace corruption, patronage, and inequality.
They hope to build a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural power house, and create more synergies with immigrant communities.
In order to achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank capital, and force a reduction of deposits from 1% of depositors who hold more than 50% of total deposits.
They support moderate currency depreciation and comprehensive improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corruption and increasing spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The infighting now over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a broader struggle in the country's search for new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a deadly threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon hangs in the balance.
